However Tyson Slocum, director of Public Citizen's Energy Program, criticized the move for letting BP 'off the hook.'

He said the company 'has failed to prove that it is a responsible contractor deserving of lucrative taxpayer deals'.

BP continues to grapple with the costs of the spill, with annual results last month showing the total charge recognised to date stood at $42.7 billion (£26.2 billion).

It is appealing against a court ruling over bogus claims on its compensation scheme and is asking for an injunction 'to prevent awards to claimants whose losses are not traceable to the spill'.

